A simple guide to text.


When using text, such as in Text.literal in a user.sendMessage, there are two(ish) types of text you can use.

Text.literal (less options, less utility, more straightforward)
Text.literal, instead of creating a string key, just literally displays the text.

example:
user.sendMessage(Text.literal("Hi! this is an example :3"));

Less options you can choose for customization but it's useful when needed.

Text.translatable (generally better)
Text.translatable is Text.literal's bigger brother, by creating a string key that can be translated in your lang file.

Example:
user.sendMessage(Text.translatable("text.examplemod.text_example"));


# TEXT UTILITIES !!!!!!

Colored text:
Text.translatable("text.examplemod.text_example").setStyle(Style.EMPTY.withColor(// insert hex code));

Default text colors, italics, strikethough, and bold
Text.translatable("text.examplemod.test_example").formatting(FORMATTED.color, bold, italic, strikethrough, etc));

Text indentation
use \n for indents

